      P("What are key aspects of Chinese cultural values reflected in language use?","Think Confucian values and social hierarchy.","Confucian influence: (1) Hierarchy and respect — formal address terms (您 nín vs. 你 nǐ for 'you'); titles used instead of names (老师 lǎoshī 'teacher'); family terms extended to non-relatives (older neighbor called '阿姨' auntie); (2) Face (面子 miànzi) — public dignity; indirect communication to avoid embarrassing others; compliments and gifts handled with ritualized modesty; (3) Group orientation — collective harmony over individual expression; (4) Food culture as social bonding — meals as primary social context; food as care; (5) Filial piety (孝顺 xiàoshun) — respect for elders and ancestors fundamental to family structure.","medium"),
      P("How does Chinese society discuss education and career expectations?","Think high-pressure academic culture.","Education culture: Gaokao (高考) — national college entrance exam; arguably most high-stakes test in the world; determines university placement; students prepare years in advance. '985' and '211' universities: elite tiers. Academic pressure: tiger parenting (严格的父母); extra tutoring (补习班); summer programs. Career expectations: traditional prestige in 'iron rice bowl' government jobs, medicine, law, finance; shifting with tech sector. Vocabulary: 内卷 (nèijuǎn — 'involution,' hyper-competitive academic/work environment); 躺平 (tǎng píng — 'lying flat,' rejecting hustle culture). These reflect generational tensions in contemporary Chinese society.","hard"),
