      P("How do you analyze a French literary text for the AP exam?","Think close reading in French.","Text analysis approach: (1) Identify genre, register, and approximate period; (2) Summarize main ideas; (3) Identify the author's purpose and audience; (4) Analyze literary devices: figures of style (métaphore, comparaison, personnification, hyperbole, ironie, antithèse, anaphore); narrative voice (narrateur omniscient, point de vue interne); time and space; (5) Identify cultural context — how does this text reflect French/Francophone culture?; (6) Analyze language level — formal vs. familiar register, vocabulary richness, sentence complexity. AP reading tasks: identify main idea, interpret vocabulary in context, make inferences, identify author's stance, analyze literary or rhetorical devices.","hard"),
      P("What are major themes in French and Francophone literature?","Think existentialism, colonialism, identity.","French literary themes: Existentialism — Sartre (L'être et le néant; Huis clos 'Hell is other people'), Camus (L'Étranger, La Peste — absurdism, authenticity). Colonialism and postcolonialism — Francophone authors from Senegal (Senghor, Sembène), Morocco (Tahar Ben Jelloun), Quebec, Caribbean (Aimé Césaire — Négritude movement). Identity and immigration — Leïla Slimani, Faïza Guène. Realism — Balzac's Comédie humaine, Flaubert's Madame Bovary (free indirect discourse, irony). Existentialist feminism — Simone de Beauvoir (Le Deuxième Sexe). Contemporary: French literature engages immigration, diversity, national identity, Europe.","hard"),
