      P("What are key cultural practices in France relevant to the AP exam?","Think laïcité, cuisine, education.","Key French cultural concepts: (1) Laïcité — strict secularism; separation of church and state (1905 law); no religious symbols in public schools; headscarf debates; differs from US religious freedom model; (2) Grande cuisine — gastronomy as cultural heritage (UNESCO recognized); French food culture (bistro, brasserie, boulangerie); AOC designations for wine and cheese; (3) Education — baccalauréat exam (like French Gaokao); Sciences Po, grandes écoles (elite institutions separate from universities); philosophy required in terminal (final) year; (4) Grèves — strikes as cultural institution; labor rights deeply valued; (5) Les grandes vacances — month-long August holiday; everything closes.","medium"),
      P("What is the Francophone world and why is it culturally significant?","Think scope and diversity.","La Francophonie: ~300 million French speakers worldwide; French is official language in 29 countries. Regions: France and Western Europe; Sub-Saharan Africa (Senegal, Côte d'Ivoire, Democratic Republic of Congo — largest French-speaking country by population); North Africa (Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia — Maghreb); Caribbean (Haiti, Guadeloupe, Martinique — French territories); Quebec; Pacific islands. Significance: French language carries different cultural histories in each region; Francophone literature explores colonial history, identity, hybridity. OIF (Organisation internationale de la Francophonie) promotes linguistic and cultural diversity. AP exam intentionally includes Francophone (non-French) perspectives.","medium"),
