      P("How does the passé simple differ from the passé composé and when is each used?","Think written vs. spoken past.","Passé simple (literary past): used in formal written narrative — novels, official histories, fairy tales (il était... puis il alla... il trouva...). Not used in spoken French (except very formal speech or parody). Passé composé: used in all spoken French AND modern informal/journalistic writing for past actions. The same 'meaning' (completed past action) is expressed differently in written formal narrative (passé simple) vs. spoken/modern (passé composé). AP reading: must recognize and understand passé simple in authentic texts. AP writing/speaking: use passé composé; passé simple in formal narrative essay shows sophistication.","hard"),
